<subSubSection id="F8414BD3575456DC70E24DBFD87FB3E9" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572" type="description">
<paragraph id="A17093E29218F936CF96C68E178A84D9" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">Description</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A2BE19595577D7D7D71A024783F78242" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">
Gregarious worms commonly known as &quot;honey comb worms&quot;. Tubes constructed with sea shells fragments, echinoderm spines debris, sand and small gravel (as well as 
<taxonomicName id="2DFFF077D39AB3B1E48B1C91E92B8E5F" genus="I." lsidName="I. cretus" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572" rank="species" species="cretus">
<emphasis id="D77AE6B20B67FEEB72C0007C583AAA18" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">I. cretus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Complete specimens 8-11.1 mm long, 1-2 mm wide, with 27-30 abdominal chaetigers and a caudal peduncle 2-3 mm long. Body divided into four specialised regions: operculum, parathorax (with three segments), abdomen and caudal region (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="D2639A634517659E0A5C3116A7B9F859" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F5999075" captionText="Figure 7. Idanthyrsus mexicanus Kirtley, 1994. A) Entire body, dorso-lateral view, B) operculum, dorsal view, C) nuchal hook, D) abdominal uncini, lateral view, E) base of outer opercular palea, F) mid-region of a outer opercular paleae, G) near distal end of outer opercular palea, H-J) inner opercular paleae. Scale bars: A) 3 mm, B) 1.5 mm, C, J) 400 x magnification, D-I) 1000 x magnification." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e57572.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/437494" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">7</figureCitation>
A). Operculum composed by a crown and a peduncle, forming two not fused lobes. Median organ short, not longer than opercular lobes. Outer palea with straight blades; base of blades with transversal thecal fringes (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="9A2A1D0042468C20EFFDBF5A16DB3C9B" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F5999075" captionText="Figure 7. Idanthyrsus mexicanus Kirtley, 1994. A) Entire body, dorso-lateral view, B) operculum, dorsal view, C) nuchal hook, D) abdominal uncini, lateral view, E) base of outer opercular palea, F) mid-region of a outer opercular paleae, G) near distal end of outer opercular palea, H-J) inner opercular paleae. Scale bars: A) 3 mm, B) 1.5 mm, C, J) 400 x magnification, D-I) 1000 x magnification." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e57572.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/437494" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">7</figureCitation>
E), lateral denticles straight (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="3BCA9D7001CB5F56654C12C502DBBCF1" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F5999075" captionText="Figure 7. Idanthyrsus mexicanus Kirtley, 1994. A) Entire body, dorso-lateral view, B) operculum, dorsal view, C) nuchal hook, D) abdominal uncini, lateral view, E) base of outer opercular palea, F) mid-region of a outer opercular paleae, G) near distal end of outer opercular palea, H-J) inner opercular paleae. Scale bars: A) 3 mm, B) 1.5 mm, C, J) 400 x magnification, D-I) 1000 x magnification." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e57572.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/437494" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">7</figureCitation>
F), longer and narrower towards tips (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="D09B3E62D27C66F1A3CCD1FB7A9FB667" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F5999075" captionText="Figure 7. Idanthyrsus mexicanus Kirtley, 1994. A) Entire body, dorso-lateral view, B) operculum, dorsal view, C) nuchal hook, D) abdominal uncini, lateral view, E) base of outer opercular palea, F) mid-region of a outer opercular paleae, G) near distal end of outer opercular palea, H-J) inner opercular paleae. Scale bars: A) 3 mm, B) 1.5 mm, C, J) 400 x magnification, D-I) 1000 x magnification." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e57572.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/437494" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">7</figureCitation>
G). Inner paleae straight with markedly, transversal thecae and pointed tips (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="80634C91A4FB12EE0EFDF5F31750AE6E" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F5999075" captionText="Figure 7. Idanthyrsus mexicanus Kirtley, 1994. A) Entire body, dorso-lateral view, B) operculum, dorsal view, C) nuchal hook, D) abdominal uncini, lateral view, E) base of outer opercular palea, F) mid-region of a outer opercular paleae, G) near distal end of outer opercular palea, H-J) inner opercular paleae. Scale bars: A) 3 mm, B) 1.5 mm, C, J) 400 x magnification, D-I) 1000 x magnification." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e57572.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/437494" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">7</figureCitation>
H-J). A pair of nuchal hooks curved (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="7E34FC1E1003B235E01CEA64AC4C0A65" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F5999075" captionText="Figure 7. Idanthyrsus mexicanus Kirtley, 1994. A) Entire body, dorso-lateral view, B) operculum, dorsal view, C) nuchal hook, D) abdominal uncini, lateral view, E) base of outer opercular palea, F) mid-region of a outer opercular paleae, G) near distal end of outer opercular palea, H-J) inner opercular paleae. Scale bars: A) 3 mm, B) 1.5 mm, C, J) 400 x magnification, D-I) 1000 x magnification." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e57572.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/437494" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">7</figureCitation>
B) without hoods or limbations on concave sides of hooks (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="97995381634C3EB54105A6D2C16EA058" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F5999075" captionText="Figure 7. Idanthyrsus mexicanus Kirtley, 1994. A) Entire body, dorso-lateral view, B) operculum, dorsal view, C) nuchal hook, D) abdominal uncini, lateral view, E) base of outer opercular palea, F) mid-region of a outer opercular paleae, G) near distal end of outer opercular palea, H-J) inner opercular paleae. Scale bars: A) 3 mm, B) 1.5 mm, C, J) 400 x magnification, D-I) 1000 x magnification." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e57572.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/437494" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">7</figureCitation>
C). Abdominal uncini with six pairs of teeth in side view (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="6BBB6CE2A31E9DC855056B950FD5B36E" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F5999075" captionText="Figure 7. Idanthyrsus mexicanus Kirtley, 1994. A) Entire body, dorso-lateral view, B) operculum, dorsal view, C) nuchal hook, D) abdominal uncini, lateral view, E) base of outer opercular palea, F) mid-region of a outer opercular paleae, G) near distal end of outer opercular palea, H-J) inner opercular paleae. Scale bars: A) 3 mm, B) 1.5 mm, C, J) 400 x magnification, D-I) 1000 x magnification." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e57572.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/437494" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">7</figureCitation>
D).
</paragraph>
